ce:section.ce:para:
The details of the preparation process and method of the Qdots-Fc nanohybrid were represented in Scheme 1
                        . First, the Qdots were synthesized using one-step thermal pyrolysis of citric acid. In a second step, a solution of 4-Ferrocenylbutanol as a battery-type electrode material in DMF was added to a suspension of Qdots in DMF and stirred at room temperature for 4 days. Functionalized Qdots with 4-ferrocenylbutanol as a Fc-based compound were obtained after centrifugation and washing process. The 4-ferrocenylbutanol was bound to the surface of the Qdots via strong interactions, including hydrogen bonding and π-π interactions (Fig. 1
                        ).

The obtained specific capacity values for all samples from the GCD curves at different current densities (2.5, 3.5, 4.5, 5, and 10 A g−1) are plotted in Fig. 11c. Among the samples, Qdots-Fc/CNT-Fe3O4(20 %) nanocomposite exhibited high specific capacities at all current densities compared to the other synthesized electrode materials (Table 1
                        ). Therefore, it can be concluded that the obtained high capacity of Qdots-Fc/CNT-Fe3O4(20 %) nanocomposite is due to the presence of the Fc ring and a reasonable amount of CNT-Fe3O4(10 %) nanohybrid in the final nanocomposite, which makes it easier for the ions to penetrate into the electrode material. In addition, compared to the Qdot-based nanocomposites reported previously, our novel Fc-modified nanocomposite shows the highest specific capacity (Table 2
                        ). The GCD and CV experiments proved that the Qdots-Fc/CNT-Fe3O4(20 %) nanocomposite had significant electrochemical behavior, superior to different electrode materials based battery-type electrodes.
